Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.00,0:00:01.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Two men in police
Dialogue: 0,0:00:01.19,0:00:02.50,Default,,0,0,0,,uniforms walked into a
Dialogue: 0,0:00:02.56,0:00:03.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Boston museum and walked
Dialogue: 0,0:00:04.06,0:00:05.08,Default,,0,0,0,,out with half a
Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.14,0:00:09.13,Default,,0,0,0,,billion dollars of masterpieces.\NEighty-one minutes. Thirteen works.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.20,0:00:13.14,Default,,0,0,0,,And more than thirty years later\N— not one has ever been found.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:15.53,0:00:16.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Walk into the Isabella
Dialogue: 0,0:00:16.91,0:00:21.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Stewart Gardner Museum in Boston\Ntoday, and you will find something that
Dialogue: 0,0:00:21.20,0:00:25.21,Default,,0,0,0,,should not be there. Or\Nrather — something that isn't.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.25,0:00:28.50,Default,,0,0,0,,On the walls, between
Dialogue: 0,0:00:28.57,0:00:30.11,Default,,0,0,0,,the paintings that remain,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:30.18,0:00:35.18,Default,,0,0,0,,hang empty frames. Gilded, ornate,\Nand holding nothing at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.94,0:00:36.96,Default,,0,0,0,,They are not a
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.03,0:00:38.81,Default,,0,0,0,,mistake, and they are not art.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:39.08,0:00:42.10,Default,,0,0,0,,They are the exact spaces\Nwhere some of the most
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.17,0:00:43.77,Default,,0,0,0,,valuable paintings on earth
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.84,0:00:48.56,Default,,0,0,0,,used to be — left hanging, deliberately,\Nas a wound the museum refuses to
Dialogue: 0,0:00:48.63,0:00:49.65,Default,,0,0,0,,cover up.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.92,0:00:54.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Because on a single night in\N1990, those frames were emptied.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:55.12,0:00:56.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Two men talked their
Dialogue: 0,0:00:56.38,0:00:59.35,Default,,0,0,0,,way through the door, tied\Nup the guards, and spent
Dialogue: 0,0:00:59.42,0:01:00.44,Default,,0,0,0,,the next hour and
Dialogue: 0,0:01:00.51,0:01:02.29,Default,,0,0,0,,twenty minutes taking thirteen
Dialogue: 0,0:01:02.36,0:01:06.47,Default,,0,0,0,,works of art worth, by common estimate,\Naround half a billion dollars.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:07.73,0:01:08.92,Default,,0,0,0,,The FBI would come
Dialogue: 0,0:01:08.99,0:01:10.01,Default,,0,0,0,,to call it the
Dialogue: 0,0:01:10.07,0:01:11.56,Default,,0,0,0,,largest property crime in
Dialogue: 0,0:01:11.63,0:01:12.70,Default,,0,0,0,,the history of the
Dialogue: 0,0:01:12.77,0:01:16.22,Default,,0,0,0,,United States. The museum calls\Nit the largest art heist in
Dialogue: 0,0:01:16.29,0:01:20.63,Default,,0,0,0,,history. And whatever you call it, it\Nshares one more title that has never
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.70,0:01:22.13,Default,,0,0,0,,changed: it is unsolved.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:23.34,0:01:24.36,Default,,0,0,0,,No one has ever
Dialogue: 0,0:01:24.43,0:01:25.68,Default,,0,0,0,,been charged with the
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.74,0:01:30.09,Default,,0,0,0,,theft. Not a single one of the thirteen\Nworks has ever been recovered. The
Dialogue: 0,0:01:30.16,0:01:31.53,Default,,0,0,0,,thieves have never been
Dialogue: 0,0:01:31.59,0:01:34.92,Default,,0,0,0,,publicly named. And the empty\Nframes still hang, waiting.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.14,0:01:41.16,Default,,0,0,0,,We are drawn to crimes that end. The\Nconfession, the trial, the verdict,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:41.58,0:01:44.74,Default,,0,0,0,,the cell door closing. This is not one
Dialogue: 0,0:01:44.81,0:01:47.25,Default,,0,0,0,,of those crimes. This is the one that got
Dialogue: 0,0:01:47.31,0:01:51.96,Default,,0,0,0,,away so completely that it has slipped\Nout of the world of police work and into
Dialogue: 0,0:01:52.02,0:01:54.82,Default,,0,0,0,,something like folklore\N— except the loss is
Dialogue: 0,0:01:54.89,0:01:57.98,Default,,0,0,0,,utterly real, and you\Ncan stand in front of it.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:58.42,0:02:03.58,Default,,0,0,0,,That is what makes the Gardner heist\Ndifferent. There is no ending to spoil.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.04,0:02:08.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Only an absence, framed in gold,\Nthat has been waiting longer than
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.19,0:02:09.26,Default,,0,0,0,,many of the people
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.32,0:02:10.69,Default,,0,0,0,,watching this have been
Dialogue: 0,0:02:10.76,0:02:11.78,Default,,0,0,0,,alive.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.34,0:02:15.20,Default,,0,0,0,,This is the story of how\Nit happened — minute by
Dialogue: 0,0:02:15.27,0:02:19.52,Default,,0,0,0,,minute. What exactly vanished, and\Nwhy it can never simply be sold.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.18,0:02:22.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Everything the FBI will\Nand won't say about
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.89,0:02:25.39,Default,,0,0,0,,who did it. And why, after more than three
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.45,0:02:27.36,Default,,0,0,0,,decades and a ten-million-dollar
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.43,0:02:30.76,Default,,0,0,0,,reward, the most famous art\Ntheft in the world is still a
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.82,0:02:32.31,Default,,0,0,0,,mystery with empty frames
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.38,0:02:33.40,Default,,0,0,0,,for an answer.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.67,0:02:38.18,Default,,0,0,0,,It begins, as the best heists do,\Nwith a quiet night and a small lie.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.76,0:02:45.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It is the early morning of March\N18th, 1990. Boston is still coming
Dialogue: 0,0:02:45.07,0:02:47.92,Default,,0,0,0,,down from St. Patrick's\NDay. The streets near the
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.99,0:02:51.21,Default,,0,0,0,,museum are empty. Inside,\Ntwo young security guards are
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.27,0:02:54.05,Default,,0,0,0,,doing the most ordinary\Nthing in the world —
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.12,0:02:55.60,Default,,0,0,0,,watching a building where
Dialogue: 0,0:02:55.67,0:02:56.92,Default,,0,0,0,,nothing ever happens.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:57.67,0:02:58.80,Default,,0,0,0,,At around half past
Dialogue: 0,0:02:58.87,0:03:00.00,Default,,0,0,0,,one in the morning,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.06,0:03:04.59,Default,,0,0,0,,a buzzer sounds at a side entrance.\NOutside stand two men in police uniforms.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.66,0:03:05.68,Default,,0,0,0,,They say they are
Dialogue: 0,0:03:05.74,0:03:10.09,Default,,0,0,0,,responding to a disturbance, a call\Nabout the grounds. They look the part.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.15,0:03:11.34,Default,,0,0,0,,They sound the part.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:12.73,0:03:17.74,Default,,0,0,0,,And here is the first hinge of the\Nwhole story — a single human decision.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:18.40,0:03:22.32,Default,,0,0,0,,One of the guards, against the\Nmuseum's own rules, buzzes them in.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:22.88,0:03:25.78,Default,,0,0,0,,It is the kind of small,\Nunderstandable mistake
Dialogue: 0,0:03:25.85,0:03:27.04,Default,,0,0,0,,anyone might make at
Dialogue: 0,0:03:27.10,0:03:28.59,Default,,0,0,0,,one-thirty in the morning
Dialogue: 0,0:03:28.66,0:03:32.59,Default,,0,0,0,,when authority is standing at the\Ndoor. He had no way of knowing it
Dialogue: 0,0:03:32.65,0:03:33.90,Default,,0,0,0,,would become the most
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.97,0:03:35.58,Default,,0,0,0,,expensive door ever opened.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:35.92,0:03:40.26,Default,,0,0,0,,It is worth pausing on why that worked,\Nbecause it is the quiet engine of
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.33,0:03:44.72,Default,,0,0,0,,the whole crime. A uniform is a\Nkind of key that opens doors no
Dialogue: 0,0:03:44.79,0:03:49.20,Default,,0,0,0,,lockpick can. We are trained,\Nall of us, to relax a little when
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.27,0:03:53.92,Default,,0,0,0,,authority arrives — to assume that the\Nperson in the uniform is the solution,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:54.34,0:03:57.40,Default,,0,0,0,,not the threat. The\Nthieves did not break in.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:57.74,0:04:01.82,Default,,0,0,0,,They were invited in, by a frightened\Nyoung man doing what most of us
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.89,0:04:02.91,Default,,0,0,0,,would do when the
Dialogue: 0,0:04:02.97,0:04:04.16,Default,,0,0,0,,police say there's a
Dialogue: 0,0:04:04.23,0:04:08.82,Default,,0,0,0,,problem. The first and biggest security\Nsystem the museum had was human trust.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.30,0:04:10.43,Default,,0,0,0,,And it was defeated
Dialogue: 0,0:04:10.50,0:04:11.52,Default,,0,0,0,,with a costume.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.86,0:04:15.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Once inside, the men move\Nquickly. They tell the
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.83,0:04:18.92,Default,,0,0,0,,guard there is a warrant for his arrest —
Dialogue: 0,0:04:18.99,0:04:23.51,Default,,0,0,0,,and ask him to step away from the only\Nalarm button in the building. He does.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.58,0:04:24.77,Default,,0,0,0,,They call the second
Dialogue: 0,0:04:24.83,0:04:29.30,Default,,0,0,0,,guard down too. And in moments, the\Ncostume drops, and the truth is obvious:
Dialogue: 0,0:04:29.38,0:04:30.63,Default,,0,0,0,,these are not police.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:32.62,0:04:34.17,Default,,0,0,0,,The guards are handcuffed,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:34.24,0:04:35.31,Default,,0,0,0,,walked down to the
Dialogue: 0,0:04:35.37,0:04:39.18,Default,,0,0,0,,basement, and bound — their wrists\Ncuffed, their heads wrapped in
Dialogue: 0,0:04:39.25,0:04:43.00,Default,,0,0,0,,duct tape. And there they will\Nstay, helpless in the dark, while
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.07,0:04:44.20,Default,,0,0,0,,above them the most
Dialogue: 0,0:04:44.26,0:04:48.13,Default,,0,0,0,,valuable art theft in history\Nunfolds in real time. Remember that:
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.20,0:04:49.57,Default,,0,0,0,,the guards were victims
Dialogue: 0,0:04:49.64,0:04:53.21,Default,,0,0,0,,too. They were tied up in a\Nbasement, not let in on a secret.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.18,0:04:56.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Now the thieves have
Dialogue: 0,0:04:56.44,0:05:00.43,Default,,0,0,0,,the run of the museum. And the\Nbuilding is watching them — silently.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.26,0:05:03.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Motion detectors quietly record
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.17,0:05:04.54,Default,,0,0,0,,their movements as they
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.61,0:05:05.80,Default,,0,0,0,,move from gallery to
Dialogue: 0,0:05:05.87,0:05:08.60,Default,,0,0,0,,gallery. There is,\Nsomewhere, a record of their
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.67,0:05:12.06,Default,,0,0,0,,footsteps that night. What\Nthere is not, is a single face.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:13.38,0:05:16.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Picture the next hour. A great museum at
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.17,0:05:18.85,Default,,0,0,0,,two in the morning, dark\Nand hushed, hung with
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.91,0:05:22.80,Default,,0,0,0,,centuries of masterpieces — and\Ntwo men moving through it alone,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.10,0:05:25.82,Default,,0,0,0,,in no apparent hurry, with all the time in
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.89,0:05:30.72,Default,,0,0,0,,the world. No alarm rang out to\Nthe police. The only witnesses were
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.79,0:05:33.88,Default,,0,0,0,,the silent sensors in the\Nceilings and the two guards
Dialogue: 0,0:05:33.95,0:05:35.20,Default,,0,0,0,,bound in the basement
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.27,0:05:39.73,Default,,0,0,0,,below, listening to footsteps overhead\Nand unable to do a single thing about
Dialogue: 0,0:05:39.80,0:05:43.31,Default,,0,0,0,,it. It is one of the eeriest\Nscenes in the history of crime:
Dialogue: 0,0:05:43.52,0:05:47.62,Default,,0,0,0,,an unhurried robbery of the\Nirreplaceable, with no one to stop it.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.29,0:05:50.31,Default,,0,0,0,,They go first to
Dialogue: 0,0:05:50.38,0:05:51.45,Default,,0,0,0,,the Dutch Room, on
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.52,0:05:54.85,Default,,0,0,0,,the second floor, where the\Ngiants hang. And here they do
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.92,0:05:59.32,Default,,0,0,0,,something that still makes art historians\Nwince. Rather than carefully lift
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.39,0:06:03.02,Default,,0,0,0,,the paintings, they cut two\Nenormous Rembrandt canvases out of
Dialogue: 0,0:06:03.09,0:06:07.19,Default,,0,0,0,,their frames. You can almost feel\Nthe violence of it — a blade against
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.26,0:06:09.58,Default,,0,0,0,,three-hundred-and-fifty-year-old paint.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:10.81,0:06:11.88,Default,,0,0,0,,They work for over
Dialogue: 0,0:06:11.95,0:06:15.05,Default,,0,0,0,,an hour. Methodical in some\Nways, baffling in others.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.36,0:06:16.97,Default,,0,0,0,,They take some masterpieces
Dialogue: 0,0:06:17.03,0:06:18.34,Default,,0,0,0,,and walk straight past
Dialogue: 0,0:06:18.41,0:06:19.72,Default,,0,0,0,,others that were worth
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.79,0:06:23.24,Default,,0,0,0,,even more. They ignore the\Nsingle most valuable painting in
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.31,0:06:24.44,Default,,0,0,0,,the building by one
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.50,0:06:27.90,Default,,0,0,0,,measure, and grab an ordinary\Nbronze eagle off a flagpole.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.96,0:06:29.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Whatever this was, it
Dialogue: 0,0:06:29.28,0:06:30.30,Default,,0,0,0,,was not the work
Dialogue: 0,0:06:30.37,0:06:31.68,Default,,0,0,0,,of refined art thieves
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.74,0:06:32.99,Default,,0,0,0,,with a shopping list.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:33.76,0:06:34.78,Default,,0,0,0,,At a quarter to
Dialogue: 0,0:06:34.85,0:06:36.10,Default,,0,0,0,,three in the morning,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:36.16,0:06:39.85,Default,,0,0,0,,they leave — making two separate\Ntrips out to a car, arms full.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.92,0:06:43.79,Default,,0,0,0,,The doors close. The museum sits\Nsilent over its two bound guards.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.20,0:06:45.22,Default,,0,0,0,,And by the time
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.29,0:06:46.66,Default,,0,0,0,,anyone arrives the next
Dialogue: 0,0:06:46.72,0:06:47.97,Default,,0,0,0,,morning to find them,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.04,0:06:49.23,Default,,0,0,0,,the thieves, and the
Dialogue: 0,0:06:49.30,0:06:50.55,Default,,0,0,0,,art, are simply gone.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.71,0:06:52.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Morning comes to the
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.97,0:06:57.61,Default,,0,0,0,,museum the way it always does. A staff\Nmember arrives for an ordinary shift and
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.68,0:06:59.94,Default,,0,0,0,,finds the unthinkable — two colleagues
Dialogue: 0,0:07:00.01,0:07:01.62,Default,,0,0,0,,handcuffed in the basement,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:01.68,0:07:06.33,Default,,0,0,0,,and upstairs, raw gaps on the walls where\Nthe world's masterpieces had hung the
Dialogue: 0,0:07:06.39,0:07:09.73,Default,,0,0,0,,night before. The police are\Ncalled. The frames are found
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.79,0:07:12.78,Default,,0,0,0,,empty, some with their\Ncanvases sliced clean away.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.46,0:07:17.34,Default,,0,0,0,,In a single overnight shift,\Nthe Isabella Stewart Gardner
Dialogue: 0,0:07:17.41,0:07:21.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Museum had become the scene of\Nthe largest art theft anyone had
Dialogue: 0,0:07:21.16,0:07:24.26,Default,,0,0,0,,ever seen — and the clock\Nthat would run for decades,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.33,0:07:26.47,Default,,0,0,0,,with no answer, had already started.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:28.56,0:07:30.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Eighty-one minutes, start to
Dialogue: 0,0:07:30.29,0:07:32.79,Default,,0,0,0,,finish. It is the last time anyone can say
Dialogue: 0,0:07:32.86,0:07:34.23,Default,,0,0,0,,for certain where those
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.30,0:07:35.49,Default,,0,0,0,,thirteen works were.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.29,0:07:38.10,Default,,0,0,0,,So what, exactly, walked out
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.17,0:07:39.36,Default,,0,0,0,,the door that night?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:41.32,0:07:45.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Thirteen works in all — and not\Nthe tidy haul you might imagine.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:45.72,0:07:50.08,Default,,0,0,0,,It is a strange, uneven list, and\Nthat strangeness is one of the great
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.15,0:07:51.34,Default,,0,0,0,,clues that has never
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.40,0:07:52.48,Default,,0,0,0,,quite been solved.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:54.01,0:07:55.03,Default,,0,0,0,,The crown of it
Dialogue: 0,0:07:55.10,0:07:56.35,Default,,0,0,0,,was a single painting
Dialogue: 0,0:07:56.42,0:07:58.92,Default,,0,0,0,,by Johannes Vermeer, called "The Concert."
Dialogue: 0,0:07:58.98,0:08:01.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Vermeer barely painted.\NOnly about three dozen of
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.95,0:08:03.08,Default,,0,0,0,,his works are known
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.14,0:08:07.31,Default,,0,0,0,,to exist anywhere on earth. "The\NConcert" is one of them — and both the
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.38,0:08:08.75,Default,,0,0,0,,museum and the FBI have
Dialogue: 0,0:08:08.81,0:08:09.88,Default,,0,0,0,,called it the most
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.95,0:08:11.86,Default,,0,0,0,,valuable unrecovered painting in
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.92,0:08:16.51,Default,,0,0,0,,the world. A quiet scene of people making\Nmusic, now itself completely silent,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:16.57,0:08:19.07,Default,,0,0,0,,its location unknown\Nfor over thirty years.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:20.78,0:08:22.24,Default,,0,0,0,,To understand why losing
Dialogue: 0,0:08:22.31,0:08:23.80,Default,,0,0,0,,that one painting matters
Dialogue: 0,0:08:23.86,0:08:27.13,Default,,0,0,0,,so much, you have to understand\Nhow little Vermeer there
Dialogue: 0,0:08:27.20,0:08:31.40,Default,,0,0,0,,is to lose. He worked slowly,\Ndied in debt, and left behind only
Dialogue: 0,0:08:31.47,0:08:32.72,Default,,0,0,0,,a few dozen paintings
Dialogue: 0,0:08:32.78,0:08:36.60,Default,,0,0,0,,in his entire life. Each one\Nthat survives is treated like a
Dialogue: 0,0:08:36.67,0:08:38.39,Default,,0,0,0,,national treasure by whatever
Dialogue: 0,0:08:38.46,0:08:42.15,Default,,0,0,0,,country is lucky enough to hold\Nit. To have one simply vanish —
Dialogue: 0,0:08:42.22,0:08:45.25,Default,,0,0,0,,cut out of the world for\Nover thirty years, its fate
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.32,0:08:49.66,Default,,0,0,0,,unknown — is not like losing a\Nvaluable object. It is like a small,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:49.73,0:08:52.23,Default,,0,0,0,,permanent hole in the\Nhistory of human art.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:53.82,0:08:56.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Then there was Rembrandt. They took his "A
Dialogue: 0,0:08:56.41,0:09:00.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Lady and Gentleman in Black,"\Nand — the one that hurts
Dialogue: 0,0:09:00.35,0:09:04.00,Default,,0,0,0,,most — "Christ in the Storm\Non the Sea of Galilee."
Dialogue: 0,0:09:04.56,0:09:08.88,Default,,0,0,0,,It is a large, dramatic painting\Nof a boat caught in a furious sea,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.26,0:09:10.28,Default,,0,0,0,,and it carries a
Dialogue: 0,0:09:10.35,0:09:14.27,Default,,0,0,0,,haunting distinction: it is the\Nonly seascape Rembrandt is known to
Dialogue: 0,0:09:14.34,0:09:18.16,Default,,0,0,0,,have ever painted. The only one.\NAnd it was cut from its frame in
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.23,0:09:19.42,Default,,0,0,0,,the dark and carried
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.48,0:09:20.50,Default,,0,0,0,,into the night.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:21.65,0:09:22.67,Default,,0,0,0,,But here is where
Dialogue: 0,0:09:22.74,0:09:27.20,Default,,0,0,0,,the list gets strange. Alongside the\NVermeer and the Rembrandts, the thieves
Dialogue: 0,0:09:27.27,0:09:30.32,Default,,0,0,0,,took five works by Degas\N— small, delicate sketches
Dialogue: 0,0:09:30.39,0:09:34.34,Default,,0,0,0,,and watercolors, not the artist's\Nmost famous or valuable pieces.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:34.80,0:09:38.04,Default,,0,0,0,,They took a Manet. And then\Nthey took two objects that
Dialogue: 0,0:09:38.11,0:09:39.36,Default,,0,0,0,,belong in an entirely
Dialogue: 0,0:09:39.42,0:09:40.85,Default,,0,0,0,,different kind of crime.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.98,0:09:43.05,Default,,0,0,0,,One was an ancient
Dialogue: 0,0:09:43.12,0:09:48.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Chinese beaker — a bronze vessel called\Na Gu, some three thousand years old.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:48.98,0:09:54.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The other was a small bronze eagle, a\Nfinial that had once topped a flagstaff
Dialogue: 0,0:09:54.07,0:09:57.92,Default,,0,0,0,,belonging to Napoleon's imperial\Nguard. Not paintings at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:58.78,0:10:00.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Odd, specific, almost personal
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.63,0:10:01.65,Default,,0,0,0,,choices.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:02.65,0:10:04.20,Default,,0,0,0,,And running underneath the
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.26,0:10:08.28,Default,,0,0,0,,whole list is a riddle. The\Nthieves walked right past works
Dialogue: 0,0:10:08.35,0:10:09.60,Default,,0,0,0,,that experts say were
Dialogue: 0,0:10:09.66,0:10:12.40,Default,,0,0,0,,more valuable than some\Nof what they took. They
Dialogue: 0,0:10:12.47,0:10:14.20,Default,,0,0,0,,spent precious minutes prying
Dialogue: 0,0:10:14.26,0:10:15.33,Default,,0,0,0,,a bronze eagle off
Dialogue: 0,0:10:15.40,0:10:19.68,Default,,0,0,0,,a pole. People who study this case\Nhave argued for decades over what that
Dialogue: 0,0:10:19.75,0:10:24.39,Default,,0,0,0,,means. Were they amateurs grabbing what\Nthey recognized? Were they working from
Dialogue: 0,0:10:24.46,0:10:28.09,Default,,0,0,0,,someone else's list? Or did the\Nstrange haul mean something we
Dialogue: 0,0:10:28.16,0:10:29.53,Default,,0,0,0,,still don't understand?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:30.34,0:10:35.06,Default,,0,0,0,,That oddness is not a small detail —\Nit is one of the few real clues the
Dialogue: 0,0:10:35.13,0:10:38.96,Default,,0,0,0,,thieves left behind. Professional\Nart thieves, the kind who steal
Dialogue: 0,0:10:39.03,0:10:42.58,Default,,0,0,0,,to order, tend to be surgical:\Nthey take the most valuable,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:42.94,0:10:44.90,Default,,0,0,0,,most portable pieces and leave
Dialogue: 0,0:10:44.97,0:10:47.94,Default,,0,0,0,,the rest. These thieves\Ndid something closer to the
Dialogue: 0,0:10:48.01,0:10:53.08,Default,,0,0,0,,opposite. They damaged masterpieces by\Ncutting them out. They skipped works of
Dialogue: 0,0:10:53.15,0:10:56.32,Default,,0,0,0,,immense value hanging nearby.\NThey spent their limited
Dialogue: 0,0:10:56.39,0:11:00.52,Default,,0,0,0,,minutes unscrewing a bronze\Neagle from a pole. Decades later,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:00.59,0:11:02.61,Default,,0,0,0,,investigators and historians still
Dialogue: 0,0:11:02.68,0:11:06.61,Default,,0,0,0,,cannot fully explain the logic —\Nand the haul itself remains one of
Dialogue: 0,0:11:06.67,0:11:08.28,Default,,0,0,0,,the most-studied riddles in
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.35,0:11:09.37,Default,,0,0,0,,the case.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:09.46,0:11:10.48,Default,,0,0,0,,And then there is
Dialogue: 0,0:11:10.55,0:11:15.18,Default,,0,0,0,,the number everyone repeats: half a\Nbillion dollars. Around five hundred
Dialogue: 0,0:11:15.62,0:11:18.38,Default,,0,0,0,,million. It is a staggering figure
Dialogue: 0,0:11:18.45,0:11:20.65,Default,,0,0,0,,— and you have to be careful with it.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:21.14,0:11:25.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Because that number is an estimate,\Nnot a price. These works are some
Dialogue: 0,0:11:25.67,0:11:27.10,Default,,0,0,0,,of the most recognizable
Dialogue: 0,0:11:27.16,0:11:31.51,Default,,0,0,0,,stolen objects on the planet. You\Ncannot walk into an auction house with a
Dialogue: 0,0:11:31.57,0:11:33.96,Default,,0,0,0,,cut-out Rembrandt. The museum itself has
Dialogue: 0,0:11:34.02,0:11:37.36,Default,,0,0,0,,said, bluntly, that it is the\Nonly buyer for these works.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:37.50,0:11:38.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Which means their true
Dialogue: 0,0:11:38.88,0:11:43.40,Default,,0,0,0,,value is almost philosophical — they\Nare priceless precisely because they can
Dialogue: 0,0:11:43.47,0:11:44.49,Default,,0,0,0,,never be sold.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:45.44,0:11:46.57,Default,,0,0,0,,In the movies there
Dialogue: 0,0:11:46.64,0:11:47.77,Default,,0,0,0,,is always a shadowy
Dialogue: 0,0:11:47.84,0:11:52.36,Default,,0,0,0,,collector — some billionaire who buys\Na stolen Vermeer to gloat over it alone
Dialogue: 0,0:11:52.43,0:11:55.94,Default,,0,0,0,,in a hidden vault. In reality,\Ninvestigators say that figure
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.01,0:12:00.53,Default,,0,0,0,,is mostly a myth. There is no orderly\Nmarket for the most recognizable stolen
Dialogue: 0,0:12:00.60,0:12:03.10,Default,,0,0,0,,paintings on earth. They are too famous to
Dialogue: 0,0:12:03.16,0:12:07.02,Default,,0,0,0,,hang, too hot to sell, and\Nworth a fortune only on paper.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:07.40,0:12:09.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Which leaves whoever ended up
Dialogue: 0,0:12:09.35,0:12:10.72,Default,,0,0,0,,holding the Gardner art
Dialogue: 0,0:12:10.78,0:12:15.16,Default,,0,0,0,,with a peculiar curse: sitting on\Nhalf a billion dollars they can never
Dialogue: 0,0:12:15.23,0:12:16.25,Default,,0,0,0,,actually spend.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:17.84,0:12:23.62,Default,,0,0,0,,That single fact — unsellable — is\Nthe key to everything that comes next.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:23.86,0:12:26.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Because it changes what\Nkind of crime this even was.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.67,0:12:29.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Most thefts are about
Dialogue: 0,0:12:30.05,0:12:31.36,Default,,0,0,0,,turning an object into
Dialogue: 0,0:12:31.42,0:12:34.34,Default,,0,0,0,,money. But thirteen of the\Nmost famous artworks in
Dialogue: 0,0:12:34.41,0:12:35.54,Default,,0,0,0,,the world cannot be
Dialogue: 0,0:12:35.60,0:12:36.85,Default,,0,0,0,,turned into money. So
Dialogue: 0,0:12:36.92,0:12:41.38,Default,,0,0,0,,either the thieves did not understand\Nthat — or the art was never really the
Dialogue: 0,0:12:41.45,0:12:45.62,Default,,0,0,0,,point. And every theory about who\Ndid this, and why, has to answer that
Dialogue: 0,0:12:45.68,0:12:46.71,Default,,0,0,0,,question.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:47.52,0:12:52.04,Default,,0,0,0,,A crime this big does not go quietly.\NThe hunt for the Gardner art became one
Dialogue: 0,0:12:52.11,0:12:53.54,Default,,0,0,0,,of the largest art-crime
Dialogue: 0,0:12:53.61,0:12:57.36,Default,,0,0,0,,investigations in FBI history,\Nand it has never formally closed.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:59.63,0:13:00.76,Default,,0,0,0,,In the early years,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.83,0:13:04.70,Default,,0,0,0,,the trail was hot and useless at\Nthe same time. Thousands of tips.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:05.20,0:13:09.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Psychics. Con men claiming they\Ncould get the paintings back —
Dialogue: 0,0:13:09.62,0:13:13.48,Default,,0,0,0,,for a price. The case drew the\Ncurious, the criminal, and the
Dialogue: 0,0:13:13.55,0:13:16.23,Default,,0,0,0,,desperate, and almost\Nnone of it led anywhere.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:17.80,0:13:21.66,Default,,0,0,0,,For a case with so few hard facts,\Nit generated an extraordinary
Dialogue: 0,0:13:21.73,0:13:26.42,Default,,0,0,0,,amount of attention. It became, over\Nthe years, the most famous unsolved art
Dialogue: 0,0:13:26.49,0:13:30.54,Default,,0,0,0,,theft in the world — the subject\Nof books, documentaries, podcasts,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:31.00,0:13:32.25,Default,,0,0,0,,and an endless stream
Dialogue: 0,0:13:32.32,0:13:34.22,Default,,0,0,0,,of armchair detectives convinced
Dialogue: 0,0:13:34.29,0:13:38.45,Default,,0,0,0,,they had cracked it. The FBI fielded\Nthousands of leads from across the
Dialogue: 0,0:13:38.52,0:13:42.08,Default,,0,0,0,,country and overseas. And that\Nis part of the tragedy of a
Dialogue: 0,0:13:42.15,0:13:46.32,Default,,0,0,0,,mystery this large: the more famous\Nit becomes, the more noise it
Dialogue: 0,0:13:46.39,0:13:47.88,Default,,0,0,0,,generates, and the harder
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.94,0:13:50.56,Default,,0,0,0,,it is to tell a real\Nwhisper from the roar of
Dialogue: 0,0:13:50.63,0:13:51.94,Default,,0,0,0,,people who simply want
Dialogue: 0,0:13:52.00,0:13:53.02,Default,,0,0,0,,to be part of
Dialogue: 0,0:13:53.09,0:13:54.11,Default,,0,0,0,,the story.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:54.18,0:13:55.78,Default,,0,0,0,,One painful thread ran back
Dialogue: 0,0:13:55.85,0:13:57.28,Default,,0,0,0,,through the museum's own
Dialogue: 0,0:13:57.35,0:14:01.51,Default,,0,0,0,,door — the guard who buzzed the men\Nin that night. Investigators looked
Dialogue: 0,0:14:01.58,0:14:03.37,Default,,0,0,0,,at him closely; that is simply
Dialogue: 0,0:14:03.43,0:14:08.01,Default,,0,0,0,,what investigators do. But it is important\Nto be precise: he was never charged
Dialogue: 0,0:14:08.08,0:14:09.33,Default,,0,0,0,,with anything, and he
Dialogue: 0,0:14:09.40,0:14:10.42,Default,,0,0,0,,was found tied up
Dialogue: 0,0:14:10.49,0:14:11.74,Default,,0,0,0,,in that basement with
Dialogue: 0,0:14:11.80,0:14:14.84,Default,,0,0,0,,the rest. Being scrutinized\Nis not the same as being
Dialogue: 0,0:14:14.90,0:14:19.19,Default,,0,0,0,,guilty, and decades of suspicion are\Ntheir own kind of sentence for a man
Dialogue: 0,0:14:19.26,0:14:20.51,Default,,0,0,0,,who was never accused
Dialogue: 0,0:14:20.57,0:14:21.59,Default,,0,0,0,,in court.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:21.66,0:14:25.35,Default,,0,0,0,,And that caution — the difference\Nbetween a suspect and a thief
Dialogue: 0,0:14:25.42,0:14:26.66,Default,,0,0,0,,— is the thread you
Dialogue: 0,0:14:26.73,0:14:27.92,Default,,0,0,0,,have to hold through
Dialogue: 0,0:14:27.98,0:14:32.57,Default,,0,0,0,,this entire case. Because over thirty\Nyears, a great many names have surfaced.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:32.63,0:14:37.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Local criminals. Mob figures. Men\Nwho claimed they knew where the art
Dialogue: 0,0:14:37.25,0:14:39.99,Default,,0,0,0,,was, or knew who took\Nit, or wanted the reward.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:41.74,0:14:42.76,Default,,0,0,0,,But here is the
Dialogue: 0,0:14:42.83,0:14:45.45,Default,,0,0,0,,discipline the facts\Ndemand. Not one of those
Dialogue: 0,0:14:45.51,0:14:50.04,Default,,0,0,0,,people has ever been charged with the\Ntheft. The FBI has never publicly named
Dialogue: 0,0:14:50.10,0:14:53.20,Default,,0,0,0,,the thieves. And the men\Nsometimes described in books
Dialogue: 0,0:14:53.26,0:14:57.31,Default,,0,0,0,,and documentaries as the likely\Nrobbers were named by journalists and
Dialogue: 0,0:14:57.38,0:15:01.37,Default,,0,0,0,,authors — not by the Bureau. Some\Nof the people who have been linked
Dialogue: 0,0:15:01.43,0:15:02.45,Default,,0,0,0,,to this case over
Dialogue: 0,0:15:02.52,0:15:03.65,Default,,0,0,0,,the years are still
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.72,0:15:07.83,Default,,0,0,0,,alive. And a theory is not a verdict.\NSo we are going to tell you what
Dialogue: 0,0:15:07.89,0:15:12.48,Default,,0,0,0,,law enforcement has actually said — and\Nstop exactly where the evidence stops.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:14.11,0:15:18.32,Default,,0,0,0,,What law enforcement has said\Ncame, most clearly, in 2013.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:18.78,0:15:22.83,Default,,0,0,0,,On the twenty-third anniversary of\Nthe heist, the FBI made a striking
Dialogue: 0,0:15:22.89,0:15:26.62,Default,,0,0,0,,announcement. It said it believed\N— with what it called a high
Dialogue: 0,0:15:26.69,0:15:29.78,Default,,0,0,0,,degree of confidence — that\Nit had finally identified
Dialogue: 0,0:15:29.85,0:15:30.87,Default,,0,0,0,,the thieves.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:31.83,0:15:32.85,Default,,0,0,0,,But it would not
Dialogue: 0,0:15:32.91,0:15:37.38,Default,,0,0,0,,name them. The FBI described them only\Nas members of a criminal organization
Dialogue: 0,0:15:37.44,0:15:38.93,Default,,0,0,0,,based in the Mid-Atlantic
Dialogue: 0,0:15:39.00,0:15:43.11,Default,,0,0,0,,states and New England. And it said\Nsomething that reframed the entire
Dialogue: 0,0:15:43.17,0:15:47.84,Default,,0,0,0,,case: the people it believed responsible\Nwere likely dead. Two years later, the
Dialogue: 0,0:15:47.91,0:15:50.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Bureau put it even more\Nplainly — the two men who
Dialogue: 0,0:15:50.83,0:15:52.14,Default,,0,0,0,,carried out the heist,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:52.21,0:15:53.58,Default,,0,0,0,,it said, were deceased.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:54.78,0:15:59.62,Default,,0,0,0,,It was a strange kind of announcement\N— a triumph and a dead end in the same
Dialogue: 0,0:15:59.69,0:16:02.62,Default,,0,0,0,,breath. The FBI was, in effect,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:03.00,0:16:06.40,Default,,0,0,0,,saying: we have solved the\Npart of the case that no longer
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.47,0:16:11.40,Default,,0,0,0,,matters, and lost the part that does.\NWe believe we know the hands that took
Dialogue: 0,0:16:11.47,0:16:14.18,Default,,0,0,0,,the paintings. We just\Ncan no longer ask them
Dialogue: 0,0:16:14.25,0:16:17.28,Default,,0,0,0,,anything — and they can no\Nlonger give the art back.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:19.00,0:16:23.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Sit with what that means. The FBI is\Ntelling you it thinks it knows who
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.41,0:16:27.10,Default,,0,0,0,,walked into that museum — and\Nthat those men are now beyond any
Dialogue: 0,0:16:27.16,0:16:30.74,Default,,0,0,0,,courtroom. The question was\Nnever really "can we catch them."
Dialogue: 0,0:16:30.96,0:16:32.06,Default,,0,0,0,,For years now, the
Dialogue: 0,0:16:32.13,0:16:36.90,Default,,0,0,0,,question has been narrower, and sadder:\Nwhere did the art go after they had it?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:38.57,0:16:40.05,Default,,0,0,0,,To shake something loose,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:40.12,0:16:41.79,Default,,0,0,0,,investigators went public in
Dialogue: 0,0:16:41.85,0:16:44.47,Default,,0,0,0,,a way they rarely do.\NThey launched an appeal
Dialogue: 0,0:16:44.54,0:16:48.58,Default,,0,0,0,,to the whole country — a dedicated\Nwebsite, images of every missing
Dialogue: 0,0:16:48.65,0:16:52.46,Default,,0,0,0,,work, even billboards in the region\Nwhere the trail had last been
Dialogue: 0,0:16:52.52,0:16:56.96,Default,,0,0,0,,warm. The message was simple, and a\Nlittle desperate: someone out there has
Dialogue: 0,0:16:57.03,0:16:58.78,Default,,0,0,0,,seen this art. On a wall.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:59.10,0:17:03.21,Default,,0,0,0,,In an attic. In a back room. We need\Nthat person to pick up the phone.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:05.05,0:17:09.88,Default,,0,0,0,,On that, the FBI offered its best answer.\NIt said the investigation traced the
Dialogue: 0,0:17:09.95,0:17:11.08,Default,,0,0,0,,stolen works out of
Dialogue: 0,0:17:11.14,0:17:15.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Boston — to Connecticut, and then to\Nthe Philadelphia area. And it said
Dialogue: 0,0:17:15.38,0:17:19.37,Default,,0,0,0,,that, roughly a decade before the\N2013 announcement, some of the art
Dialogue: 0,0:17:19.43,0:17:22.59,Default,,0,0,0,,had been offered for sale\Nin Philadelphia. After that,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:22.65,0:17:27.20,Default,,0,0,0,,the trail goes cold. The FBI has\Nsaid, in effect: we followed it this
Dialogue: 0,0:17:27.27,0:17:30.80,Default,,0,0,0,,far, and then we lost it. We\Ndo not know where it is now.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:32.62,0:17:33.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Think about how a
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.71,0:17:34.90,Default,,0,0,0,,trail like that goes
Dialogue: 0,0:17:34.96,0:17:38.00,Default,,0,0,0,,cold. Stolen art that cannot\Nbe sold openly tends to
Dialogue: 0,0:17:38.07,0:17:39.38,Default,,0,0,0,,drift through a hidden
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.44,0:17:42.78,Default,,0,0,0,,world — used as collateral,\Nas a favor, as a chip in some
Dialogue: 0,0:17:42.84,0:17:45.52,Default,,0,0,0,,other deal, passed from\Nhand to hand by people
Dialogue: 0,0:17:45.59,0:17:49.34,Default,,0,0,0,,who have every reason never to\Ntalk. Each time it changes hands,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:49.40,0:17:50.71,Default,,0,0,0,,the knowledge of where
Dialogue: 0,0:17:50.78,0:17:52.92,Default,,0,0,0,,it sits gets thinner, and the people
Dialogue: 0,0:17:52.99,0:17:57.51,Default,,0,0,0,,who hold the secret get fewer. By the\Ntime the FBI traced it to Philadelphia,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:57.58,0:18:01.21,Default,,0,0,0,,it may already have moved again.\NA painting can be hidden in a
Dialogue: 0,0:18:01.28,0:18:05.92,Default,,0,0,0,,single room. The truth about where it\Nwent can be hidden inside a single person
Dialogue: 0,0:18:05.99,0:18:07.01,Default,,0,0,0,,— and people do
Dialogue: 0,0:18:07.08,0:18:08.10,Default,,0,0,0,,not last forever.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:08.29,0:18:09.31,Default,,0,0,0,,And there is one
Dialogue: 0,0:18:09.38,0:18:10.75,Default,,0,0,0,,more twist that changes
Dialogue: 0,0:18:10.82,0:18:11.89,Default,,0,0,0,,the whole shape of
Dialogue: 0,0:18:11.95,0:18:16.00,Default,,0,0,0,,the hunt. The statute of limitations\Non the theft itself has expired.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:16.07,0:18:20.35,Default,,0,0,0,,In plain terms: even if you walked\Ninto an FBI office today and confessed
Dialogue: 0,0:18:20.42,0:18:24.02,Default,,0,0,0,,to robbing the Gardner Museum\Nin 1990, you could not be
Dialogue: 0,0:18:24.09,0:18:27.18,Default,,0,0,0,,prosecuted for the theft.\NThe clock ran out long ago.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:28.84,0:18:32.72,Default,,0,0,0,,At first that sounds like a\Nfailure. But it is actually a tool.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:32.79,0:18:37.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Because it means the people who matter\Nmost now are not the thieves — they are
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.53,0:18:39.07,Default,,0,0,0,,whoever is quietly holding
Dialogue: 0,0:18:39.14,0:18:42.77,Default,,0,0,0,,the art. And to those people,\Nthe message from prosecutors has
Dialogue: 0,0:18:42.84,0:18:46.65,Default,,0,0,0,,been remarkably open: we are far\Nmore interested in getting these
Dialogue: 0,0:18:46.71,0:18:47.79,Default,,0,0,0,,works back than in
Dialogue: 0,0:18:47.85,0:18:48.87,Default,,0,0,0,,putting you in a
Dialogue: 0,0:18:48.94,0:18:52.45,Default,,0,0,0,,cell. They have signaled a\Nwillingness to consider immunity.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:52.52,0:18:54.24,Default,,0,0,0,,There is a ten-million-dollar
Dialogue: 0,0:18:54.31,0:18:56.81,Default,,0,0,0,,reward. You would not\Neven have to hand the
Dialogue: 0,0:18:56.88,0:18:58.37,Default,,0,0,0,,paintings over in person.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:59.18,0:19:00.25,Default,,0,0,0,,And the museum has
Dialogue: 0,0:19:00.32,0:19:04.42,Default,,0,0,0,,tried to make saying something as\Neasy and as safe as it possibly can.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:04.90,0:19:08.35,Default,,0,0,0,,The ten-million-dollar reward\Nis for information that leads
Dialogue: 0,0:19:08.42,0:19:13.54,Default,,0,0,0,,to the recovery of all thirteen works\Nin good condition. You would not have
Dialogue: 0,0:19:13.61,0:19:14.63,Default,,0,0,0,,to march into a
Dialogue: 0,0:19:14.69,0:19:19.16,Default,,0,0,0,,police station. You could work through\Na lawyer, protect your identity, keep
Dialogue: 0,0:19:19.22,0:19:22.97,Default,,0,0,0,,your distance. The whole offer\Nis built around one almost gentle
Dialogue: 0,0:19:23.04,0:19:27.58,Default,,0,0,0,,idea: we are not hunting you — we just\Nwant them back. Bring the art home,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:27.90,0:19:31.50,Default,,0,0,0,,and there is a fortune, and\Na measure of safety, waiting.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:33.42,0:19:34.73,Default,,0,0,0,,The whole machinery of
Dialogue: 0,0:19:34.80,0:19:38.91,Default,,0,0,0,,the law, in other words, has been\Nquietly rebuilt around a single goal
Dialogue: 0,0:19:39.42,0:19:40.44,Default,,0,0,0,,— not justice for
Dialogue: 0,0:19:40.51,0:19:41.64,Default,,0,0,0,,the theft, which is
Dialogue: 0,0:19:41.70,0:19:46.11,Default,,0,0,0,,now impossible, but the return of\Nthirteen objects that cannot be replaced.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:47.65,0:19:51.36,Default,,0,0,0,,So if the FBI believes it knows\Nwho did it, and there is a
Dialogue: 0,0:19:51.43,0:19:56.07,Default,,0,0,0,,fortune waiting for whoever returns the\Nart, and no one even has to fear prison
Dialogue: 0,0:19:56.14,0:19:58.88,Default,,0,0,0,,for the theft — why are\Nthe frames still empty?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:01.23,0:20:05.10,Default,,0,0,0,,That is the real mystery of the\NGardner case. Not so much whodunit
Dialogue: 0,0:20:05.96,0:20:08.74,Default,,0,0,0,,— but why, after all\Nthis, nothing comes back.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:10.49,0:20:11.74,Default,,0,0,0,,There are really only
Dialogue: 0,0:20:11.81,0:20:13.23,Default,,0,0,0,,a few possibilities, and
Dialogue: 0,0:20:13.30,0:20:14.32,Default,,0,0,0,,none of them is
Dialogue: 0,0:20:14.39,0:20:15.41,Default,,0,0,0,,comfortable.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:15.71,0:20:21.02,Default,,0,0,0,,The first is the simplest, and the\Nworst. The art may be gone — destroyed.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:22.10,0:20:25.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Stolen goods this hot are\Na danger to everyone who
Dialogue: 0,0:20:25.13,0:20:29.68,Default,,0,0,0,,touches them. Someone, at some point\Nin three decades, may have decided that
Dialogue: 0,0:20:29.75,0:20:33.86,Default,,0,0,0,,the safest thing to do with a\Npainting no one can sell is to
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.93,0:20:35.18,Default,,0,0,0,,make it disappear for
Dialogue: 0,0:20:35.24,0:20:39.59,Default,,0,0,0,,good. If that is true, the empty frames\Nare not waiting for anything. They
Dialogue: 0,0:20:39.66,0:20:40.68,Default,,0,0,0,,are gravestones.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:41.59,0:20:42.66,Default,,0,0,0,,The second is that
Dialogue: 0,0:20:42.73,0:20:47.34,Default,,0,0,0,,the art is still out there — sitting\Nin an attic, a storage unit, a basement
Dialogue: 0,0:20:48.91,0:20:49.93,Default,,0,0,0,,— held by someone
Dialogue: 0,0:20:49.99,0:20:53.86,Default,,0,0,0,,who inherited it, or is afraid of\Nit, or simply does not know what
Dialogue: 0,0:20:53.93,0:20:58.27,Default,,0,0,0,,they have. Masterpieces have resurfaced\Nbefore, decades later, in stranger
Dialogue: 0,0:20:58.34,0:21:03.00,Default,,0,0,0,,places. The reward exists precisely\Nbecause the FBI and the museum believe
Dialogue: 0,0:21:03.07,0:21:04.09,Default,,0,0,0,,this is possible.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:05.62,0:21:06.64,Default,,0,0,0,,And the third is
Dialogue: 0,0:21:06.71,0:21:11.23,Default,,0,0,0,,the quiet ache underneath the whole case\N— that the few people who truly knew
Dialogue: 0,0:21:11.30,0:21:12.37,Default,,0,0,0,,where it went have
Dialogue: 0,0:21:12.43,0:21:13.57,Default,,0,0,0,,taken the answer to
Dialogue: 0,0:21:13.63,0:21:17.50,Default,,0,0,0,,their graves. If the thieves are\Ndead, and the middlemen are dead,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:17.57,0:21:18.76,Default,,0,0,0,,then the location of
Dialogue: 0,0:21:18.83,0:21:22.87,Default,,0,0,0,,half a billion dollars in art may\Nnow exist in no living mind at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:24.35,0:21:25.72,Default,,0,0,0,,The leading theory, the
Dialogue: 0,0:21:25.79,0:21:29.72,Default,,0,0,0,,one law enforcement's own statements\Npoint toward, is that this was
Dialogue: 0,0:21:29.78,0:21:34.01,Default,,0,0,0,,the work of organized crime — local\Ncriminals who saw an easy target and
Dialogue: 0,0:21:34.86,0:21:39.26,Default,,0,0,0,,a famous prize, and who may\Nhave grabbed the art with only
Dialogue: 0,0:21:41.66,0:21:47.18,Default,,0,0,0,,a vague idea of how to ever turn it
Dialogue: 0,0:21:49.06,0:21:53.80,Default,,0,0,0,,into money. That would explain\Nthe strange, amateurish haul.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:53.90,0:21:58.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It would explain why nothing\Nwas ever quietly sold.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:58.08,0:22:03.76,Default,,0,0,0,,And it would explain the silence: in that\Nworld, the people who know things are
Dialogue: 0,0:22:03.83,0:22:05.14,Default,,0,0,0,,exactly the people who
Dialogue: 0,0:22:05.20,0:22:09.25,Default,,0,0,0,,never, ever say them. If that is\Nwhat happened, then the art was less
Dialogue: 0,0:22:09.32,0:22:12.95,Default,,0,0,0,,a treasure than a curse — too\Nhot to sell, too famous to show,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:13.02,0:22:14.62,Default,,0,0,0,,too valuable to throw away.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:14.69,0:22:15.94,Default,,0,0,0,,And woven through all
Dialogue: 0,0:22:16.01,0:22:17.03,Default,,0,0,0,,of it are the
Dialogue: 0,0:22:17.09,0:22:18.76,Default,,0,0,0,,smaller mysteries that never
Dialogue: 0,0:22:18.83,0:22:22.81,Default,,0,0,0,,resolved. Like the strange detail\Nfrom inside the museum that night:
Dialogue: 0,0:22:22.88,0:22:24.61,Default,,0,0,0,,according to the museum's own
Dialogue: 0,0:22:24.67,0:22:29.14,Default,,0,0,0,,security chief, the motion sensors\Nrecorded no one but a guard ever entering
Dialogue: 0,0:22:29.20,0:22:30.28,Default,,0,0,0,,one of the rooms a
Dialogue: 0,0:22:30.34,0:22:34.63,Default,,0,0,0,,painting was taken from. A work vanished\Nfrom a space the system says the
Dialogue: 0,0:22:34.69,0:22:36.24,Default,,0,0,0,,thieves never walked into.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:36.31,0:22:39.88,Default,,0,0,0,,A small, maddening puzzle,\Ndecades old, with no clean answer.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:39.95,0:22:40.97,Default,,0,0,0,,And there is a
Dialogue: 0,0:22:41.03,0:22:42.28,Default,,0,0,0,,human cost to an open
Dialogue: 0,0:22:42.35,0:22:43.54,Default,,0,0,0,,wound like this that
Dialogue: 0,0:22:43.61,0:22:44.63,Default,,0,0,0,,is easy to forget
Dialogue: 0,0:22:44.69,0:22:47.08,Default,,0,0,0,,behind the half-billion-dollar headline.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:47.14,0:22:50.89,Default,,0,0,0,,A museum that has spent more than\Nthree decades as the site of a
Dialogue: 0,0:22:50.96,0:22:54.71,Default,,0,0,0,,famous loss. A city that quietly\Nadopted the mystery as its own.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:54.78,0:22:56.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Investigators who gave years
Dialogue: 0,0:22:56.51,0:23:00.38,Default,,0,0,0,,of their careers to a case that\Nnever let them reach the end. And,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:00.45,0:23:03.66,Default,,0,0,0,,somewhere, two men who were\Nyoung guards on an ordinary
Dialogue: 0,0:23:03.73,0:23:05.33,Default,,0,0,0,,shift and have carried that
Dialogue: 0,0:23:05.40,0:23:06.59,Default,,0,0,0,,night with them ever
Dialogue: 0,0:23:06.66,0:23:11.00,Default,,0,0,0,,since. The empty frames are a loss for\Nthe history of art. They are also a
Dialogue: 0,0:23:11.07,0:23:12.56,Default,,0,0,0,,loss measured in ordinary
Dialogue: 0,0:23:12.62,0:23:13.64,Default,,0,0,0,,lives.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:13.71,0:23:14.78,Default,,0,0,0,,This is what makes
Dialogue: 0,0:23:14.85,0:23:16.46,Default,,0,0,0,,the Gardner heist different
Dialogue: 0,0:23:16.52,0:23:20.39,Default,,0,0,0,,from the crimes that get tidy\Nendings. There is no trial to watch.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:20.46,0:23:21.59,Default,,0,0,0,,No verdict to argue
Dialogue: 0,0:23:21.66,0:23:25.88,Default,,0,0,0,,about. No moment where a detective\Nlays it all out and the pieces click.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:25.95,0:23:26.97,Default,,0,0,0,,There is only a
Dialogue: 0,0:23:27.04,0:23:30.79,Default,,0,0,0,,slowly cooling trail, a list of\Nnames that never became charges,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:30.86,0:23:31.99,Default,,0,0,0,,and a building that
Dialogue: 0,0:23:32.05,0:23:33.24,Default,,0,0,0,,decided to leave the
Dialogue: 0,0:23:33.31,0:23:34.33,Default,,0,0,0,,wound open.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:34.40,0:23:35.42,Default,,0,0,0,,You would think a
Dialogue: 0,0:23:35.48,0:23:37.51,Default,,0,0,0,,ten-million-dollar reward would be
Dialogue: 0,0:23:37.57,0:23:41.62,Default,,0,0,0,,enough to break almost any silence.\NThe fact that it hasn't tells you
Dialogue: 0,0:23:41.69,0:23:43.23,Default,,0,0,0,,something cold about where
Dialogue: 0,0:23:43.30,0:23:44.32,Default,,0,0,0,,the art may have
Dialogue: 0,0:23:44.39,0:23:48.44,Default,,0,0,0,,gone. Either the people who could\Nclaim it are dead, or they are more
Dialogue: 0,0:23:48.50,0:23:50.17,Default,,0,0,0,,frightened of something than
Dialogue: 0,0:23:50.24,0:23:51.37,Default,,0,0,0,,they are tempted by
Dialogue: 0,0:23:51.43,0:23:55.01,Default,,0,0,0,,ten million dollars, or there\Nis simply nothing left to bring
Dialogue: 0,0:23:55.07,0:23:59.65,Default,,0,0,0,,back. A reward that large, unclaimed for\Nthis long, stops being just an offer.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:59.72,0:24:03.83,Default,,0,0,0,,It becomes evidence — that whatever\Nhappened to the Gardner art, it is
Dialogue: 0,0:24:03.90,0:24:05.32,Default,,0,0,0,,buried deeper than money
Dialogue: 0,0:24:05.39,0:24:06.41,Default,,0,0,0,,can reach.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:06.48,0:24:10.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Because that was a choice. The museum\Ncould have quietly filled those spaces
Dialogue: 0,0:24:11.01,0:24:14.76,Default,,0,0,0,,— moved a painting over, hung\Nsomething new, let the walls heal.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:14.83,0:24:17.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Instead, the empty frames\Nstay exactly where the
Dialogue: 0,0:24:17.69,0:24:21.92,Default,,0,0,0,,stolen works hung. In part because\NIsabella Stewart Gardner's own wishes
Dialogue: 0,0:24:21.98,0:24:24.36,Default,,0,0,0,,asked that her collection be kept as she
Dialogue: 0,0:24:24.43,0:24:26.93,Default,,0,0,0,,arranged it. And in part as something more
Dialogue: 0,0:24:27.00,0:24:29.50,Default,,0,0,0,,deliberate: a refusal to pretend it didn't
Dialogue: 0,0:24:29.57,0:24:33.91,Default,,0,0,0,,happen, and a standing, public hope\Nthat one day the frames will be filled
Dialogue: 0,0:24:33.98,0:24:35.00,Default,,0,0,0,,again.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:35.06,0:24:36.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Every visitor who stands
Dialogue: 0,0:24:36.56,0:24:37.58,Default,,0,0,0,,in front of one
Dialogue: 0,0:24:37.65,0:24:38.72,Default,,0,0,0,,of those frames is
Dialogue: 0,0:24:38.78,0:24:43.37,Default,,0,0,0,,looking at the same thing the thieves\Nleft behind. Not a painting. A question.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:43.43,0:24:44.74,Default,,0,0,0,,More than thirty years
Dialogue: 0,0:24:44.81,0:24:46.06,Default,,0,0,0,,on, the Gardner heist
Dialogue: 0,0:24:46.13,0:24:49.94,Default,,0,0,0,,has outlived almost everyone\Nconnected to it. The guards grew up.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:50.00,0:24:52.74,Default,,0,0,0,,The lead investigators\Nretired. The men the FBI
Dialogue: 0,0:24:52.81,0:24:55.49,Default,,0,0,0,,believes did it are, by\Nits own account, gone.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:55.55,0:24:59.12,Default,,0,0,0,,And still, the most valuable\Nstolen art on earth is out there
Dialogue: 0,0:24:59.19,0:25:02.35,Default,,0,0,0,,somewhere — or it isn't —\Nand the frames keep waiting.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:04.01,0:25:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It is tempting to want a\Nvillain, a name, a face to blame.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:08.50,0:25:09.81,Default,,0,0,0,,But the honest version
Dialogue: 0,0:25:09.88,0:25:14.96,Default,,0,0,0,,of this story is harder, and stranger.\NIt is a crime that has slipped past
Dialogue: 0,0:25:15.03,0:25:18.18,Default,,0,0,0,,the reach of the law, past\Nthe lives of the people who
Dialogue: 0,0:25:18.25,0:25:22.90,Default,,0,0,0,,committed it, and into something closer\Nto a legend — except that the loss
Dialogue: 0,0:25:22.97,0:25:26.95,Default,,0,0,0,,is completely real, and it is hanging\Non a wall in Boston right now.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:28.50,0:25:29.52,Default,,0,0,0,,And maybe that is
Dialogue: 0,0:25:29.59,0:25:34.06,Default,,0,0,0,,why it holds us. We are used to stories\Nthat close. This one simply refuses.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:34.84,0:25:38.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Somewhere, perhaps, a Vermeer\Nis rolled in a tube in the dark.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:39.02,0:25:44.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Or perhaps it is ash. We do not know.\NAnd the not-knowing is the whole
Dialogue: 0,0:25:44.25,0:25:49.10,Default,,0,0,0,,point — a half-billion-dollar question,\Nwith empty gold frames where the
Dialogue: 0,0:25:49.17,0:25:50.19,Default,,0,0,0,,answer should be.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:51.65,0:25:53.14,Default,,0,0,0,,There is something almost
Dialogue: 0,0:25:53.20,0:25:56.78,Default,,0,0,0,,unbearable about a loss that\Njust stays open. A murder gets a
Dialogue: 0,0:25:56.84,0:26:01.48,Default,,0,0,0,,trial. A war gets a treaty. Even\Nmost thefts end with a recovery or
Dialogue: 0,0:26:01.55,0:26:06.06,Default,,0,0,0,,an arrest or, at least, a closed\Nfile. The Gardner heist gives
Dialogue: 0,0:26:06.13,0:26:08.86,Default,,0,0,0,,you none of that. It\Nasks you to live with not
Dialogue: 0,0:26:08.93,0:26:13.98,Default,,0,0,0,,knowing — to accept that one ordinary\NMarch night, thirteen pieces of the
Dialogue: 0,0:26:14.05,0:26:15.54,Default,,0,0,0,,world's memory walked out
Dialogue: 0,0:26:15.60,0:26:17.92,Default,,0,0,0,,a door, and that they may be sitting in
Dialogue: 0,0:26:17.99,0:26:22.10,Default,,0,0,0,,the dark somewhere right now, or may\Nbe gone forever, and that both of
Dialogue: 0,0:26:22.16,0:26:25.26,Default,,0,0,0,,those things feel equally\Npossible and equally wrong.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:27.05,0:26:32.12,Default,,0,0,0,,If those frames ever fill again, it will\Nlikely be because one ordinary person
Dialogue: 0,0:26:32.62,0:26:33.64,Default,,0,0,0,,— someone who saw
Dialogue: 0,0:26:33.70,0:26:39.36,Default,,0,0,0,,something, in an attic, a storage unit,\Na quiet back room — finally decided to
Dialogue: 0,0:26:39.43,0:26:44.06,Default,,0,0,0,,make a call. After all this\Ntime, that is still how it ends.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:44.52,0:26:47.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Not with a detective. With a witness.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:48.94,0:26:53.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So while those frames wait — do one\Nsmall thing that actually helps.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:53.38,0:26:54.88,Default,,0,0,0,,If a mystery this big
Dialogue: 0,0:26:54.95,0:27:00.14,Default,,0,0,0,,should never be allowed to fade, tap\Nlike, and subscribe. It keeps stories like
Dialogue: 0,0:27:00.21,0:27:01.88,Default,,0,0,0,,this alive, and it costs you
Dialogue: 0,0:27:01.95,0:27:03.20,Default,,0,0,0,,nothing but a second.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:04.66,0:27:05.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Because the next call
Dialogue: 0,0:27:05.97,0:27:07.34,Default,,0,0,0,,might come from someone
Dialogue: 0,0:27:07.41,0:27:11.40,Default,,0,0,0,,who watched a video just like this\None. Stay with us — next time, we
Dialogue: 0,0:27:11.47,0:27:12.72,Default,,0,0,0,,open another case the
Dialogue: 0,0:27:12.78,0:27:14.21,Default,,0,0,0,,world was never supposed
Dialogue: 0,0:27:14.28,0:27:16.08,Default,,0,0,0,,to forget.
